def: White, glowing, or luminous, with intense heat; as,incandescent carbon or platinum; hence, clear; shining; brilliant.Holy Scripture become resplendent; or, as one might say, incandescentthroughout. I. Taylor.Incandescent lamp or light (Elec.), a kind of lamp in which the lightis produced by a thin filament of conducting material, usuallycarbon, contained in a vacuum, and heated to incandescence by anelectric current, as in the Edison lamp; -- called also incandescencelamp, and glowlamp.
The quality or state of being superabundant; a superabundantquantity; redundancy; excess.
To inform, fill, or animate, excessively. [R.] Johnson.
A monk of the reformed branch of the Benedictine Order, foundedin 912 at Cluny (or Clugny) in France.-- Also used as a.
A menace or threat. [Obs.] Jer. Taylor.
Having the inflections of, or construed with, words pertainingespecially to male beings, as distinguished from feminine and neuter.See Gender.-- Mas"cu*line*ly, adv.-- Mas"cu*line*ness, n.
That in which anything is packed; bagging, as for hops. [Obs.]Halliwell.
The process of converting, or of being converted, into afossil.
An error in chronology, consisting in an event being datedbefore the actual time.
A change, as in the use of words; a metaphor.
